  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Developments\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) in the US\n- First international guidelines by Financial Action Task Force (FATF) in 1989\n- Focused primarily on reporting large cash transactions\n\n2. Key Milestones\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) expanded financial monitoring\n- Enhanced customer due diligence requirements\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n- Strengthened international cooperation\n\n3. Modern Regulatory Approaches\n- Risk-based compliance frameworks\n- Enhanced digital transaction monitoring\n- Cryptocurrency and digital asset regulations\n- Beneficial ownership transparency requirements\n\n4. Global Coordination\n- Standardized international anti-money laundering (AML) protocols\n- Cross-border information sharing\n- Coordinated enforcement mechanisms\n\n5. Technological Integration\n- Advanced data analytics\n- Machine learning for transaction pattern detection\n- Automated suspicious activity reporting\n- Real-time monitoring systems\n\n6. Emerging Trends\n- Blockchain traceability\n- Artificial intelligence in financial crime detection\n- Increased regulatory scrutiny of emerging financial technologies\n\nThese developments reflect increasingly sophisticated approaches to preventing financial crimes.",
